\begin_layout Title
Multiplication Theorem (Scratchpad)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Linas Vepstas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
April 2026
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
A short revisit of the Bernoulli Operator diary,
 focusing on the multiplication theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a scratchpad,
 i.e.
 I'm going to write some relatively trivial algebraic manipulations here,
 instead of on a piece of paper.
 Mostly because this is editable in the way that paper is not.
 I expect zero deep results.
 I do expect to answer some questions I've posed for myself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Multiplication Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Write the Bernoulli operator as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{k}g\right]\left(x\right)=\sum_{m=0}^{k-1}g\left(\frac{x+m}{k}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Write a discrete Fourier series for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\left(x\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}f\left(n\right)\exp\left(2\pi inx\right)
\]

\end_inset

Note this is not the sum runs only over the non–negative 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and so this is NOT the Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}\left(\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging through
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{k}g\right]\left(x\right) & =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}f\left(n\right)\sum_{m=0}^{k-1}\exp\left(2\pi in\frac{x+m}{k}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}f\left(n\right)\exp\left(\frac{2\pi inx}{k}\right)\sum_{m=0}^{k-1}\exp\left(\frac{2\pi inm}{k}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}f\left(n\right)\exp\left(\frac{2\pi inx}{k}\right)\begin{cases}
k & \mbox{for integer }p=n/k\\
0 & \mbox{otherwise}
\end{cases}\\
 & =k\sum_{p=0}^{\infty}f\left(kp\right)\exp\left(2\pi ipx\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Then,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is completely multiplicative,
 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(kp\right)=f\left(k\right)f\left(p\right)$
\end_inset

 then we arrive at the classical multiplication theorem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{m=0}^{k-1}g\left(\frac{x+m}{k}\right)=kf\left(k\right)g\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Generlization?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How might this generalize?
 There are two directions to go in.
 One is to replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{m}\exp$
\end_inset

 by some multiplicative character,
 in general.
 Another is to replace it by something else that already obeys the multiplication theorem.
 Lets try the second one first.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\left(x\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}f\left(n\right)h\left(nx\right)
\]

\end_inset

Then replicating the previous gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{k}g\right]\left(x\right) & =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}f\left(n\right)\sum_{m=0}^{k-1}h\left(\frac{nx}{k}+\frac{nm}{k}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

There's only one function that obeys 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x+y\right)=h\left(x\right)h\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 and that is the exponential.
 This holds even if we relax the domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

anything
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (any space or manifold).
 This has the form of a group homomorphism;
 the plus sign implies its some abelian group.
 But then we'd have to have 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be group valued as well.
 Down this path lies generic group and ring theory,
 and that's a potentially bottomless pit which does not seem to promise interesting results.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another possible exception might be to replace the Fourier xform by the Gelfand representation on C*-algebras,
 but this again wanders into territory that is quite different,
 and has it's own distinct set of rules.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is continuous,
 this exhausts all the possibilities.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is not continuous,
 then there's some uncountable set of possibilities.
 What are these?
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another possibility is to wrote 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x+a\right)=h\left(x\right)r\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

,
 which seems like it should open up more possibilities,
 but doesn't.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another possibility is to explore 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

–adic fields,
 so more constrained than rings in general,
 but less constrained than 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Completely mutliplicative functions?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 obeys the multiplication theorem whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(n\right)$
\end_inset

 is completely multiplicative,
 and when the Fourier sum converges.
 Completely multiplicative functions are completely determined by their values on the prime numbers.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(n\right)=p_{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

'th prime number so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(1\right)=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(2\right)=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(0\right)=1$
\end_inset

 if that becomes necessary.
 Why the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

?
 Because prime numbers are 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

andom and because it looks like the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 for any sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ c_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(n\right)=\begin{cases}
c_{m} & \mbox{for }n\mbox{ prime and }\rho\left(m\right)=n\\
f^{a_{1}}\left(p_{1}\right)\cdots f^{a_{k}}\left(p_{k}\right) & \mbox{for composite }n=p_{1}^{a_{1}}\cdots p_{k}^{a_{k}}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

The question then becomes:
 what is the space of sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ c_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined?
 This is tricky in several ways.
 Do we want 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 to be defined on the unit interval?
 The whole real line?
 The entire complex plane?
 The complex unit disk?
 The upper half–plane?
 And what type of convergence do we require?
 Hardy space,
 for the last two?
 Hilbert space,
 for the former?
 Perhaps some Banach 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{p}$
\end_inset

?
 A space of continuous functions?
 A space of once–differentiable Or maybe just the space of analytic functions,
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is analytic (infinite–polynomial) on some disk?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All the classical functions are analytic,
 so this is a good place to start.
 However,
 when I was younger,
 I failed to appreciate just how 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

small
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the space of analytic functions are,
 as compared to,
 for example,
 a Hilbert space.
 This difference is striking,
 once you see it;
 its a bit like 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\subset\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 but the differences between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 are striking.
 In the past,
 I have found the differences between the spectral theory of analytic functions and square–integrable functions to be wildly confusing;
 a confusion I never entirely cleared up.
 A bit lat to make amends,
 but,
 oh well.
 (Specifically:
 the spectrum of the Bernoulli operator being discrete when limited to polynomials,
 but continuous when considering the square–integrable functions.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Still (and I ask google LLM at this point) I am reminded of the Stone–Weierstrass theorem;
 this says that the analytic functions are dense in the space of continuous functions,
 i.e.
 that any continuous function can be approximated by polynomials.
 But we also have that the analytic functions are dense in the usual Hilbert spaces.
 But this is (only) for compact spaces;
 the LLM reminds me:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\series bold
\emph on
Not Dense in Bergman Space
\series default
:
 The space of analytic functions 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{2}\left(U\right)$
\end_inset

 (the Bergman space) on an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 is a closed subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}\left(U\right)$
\end_inset

,
 meaning the analytic functions are not dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}\left(U\right)$
\end_inset

 itself.
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are also several things that bug me.
 One is ringing (Gibbs phenomenon).
 This is a finite fourier series converging to a discontinuity.
 It does converge in the 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}$
\end_inset

 norm,
 because the energy contained in the ringing decreases as 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N$
\end_inset

 in the number of terms (because the width of the rings decreases as 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N$
\end_inset

).
 There is no uniform convergence (the 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 norm);
 that is,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert f-S_{N}\right\Vert _{\infty}$
\end_inset

 remains finite even as 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

 for partial sums 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{N}$
\end_inset

,
 due to the Gibbs phenomenon.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stone–Weierstrass says that the polynomials are dense in the space of continuous functions with compact support.
 Likewise,
 finite Fourier series are dense in the space of continuous functions.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Dense
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 means uniform convergence:
 the polynomials converge uniformly to continuous functions.
 For discontinuous functions,
 one gets convergence only in the 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}$
\end_inset

 norm.
 But also the continuous functions with compact support are dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

